{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T12:36:02.221561+00:00", "modified": "2024-08-29T12:36:06.655580+00:00", "id": 13479338, "conceptrecid": "13479337", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13479338", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13479337", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13479338", "metadata": {"title": "Effects of land\u2010use changes on Brazilian bats: a review of current knowledge", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13479338", "publication_date": "2021", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Abstract\n            \n              \n                \n                  One third of Brazil has been converted to human\u2010modified lands, emphasising the need to understand biodiversity's responses to land\u2010use changes. To address this issue, we reviewed 53 studies on the effects of land\u2010use changes on bats in the country from 1990 to 2018. Bats were chosen because they contribute towards numerous ecosystem services, including seed dispersal and insect control.\n                \n                \n                  For each study, we obtained data on the biome where fieldwork was conducted, participating institutes, sampling method, sampling effort, main results and academic impact. Spatial scales of studies were divided into 'local', 'fragment', 'landscape' or 'metapopulation'.\n                \n                \n                  Our results indicate an increasing interest in bats and land\u2010use changes in Brazil over time; however, no trend in academic impact factor was found. Studies carried out in the Atlantic Forest were the most common, appearing earlier in the literature, but studies in Amazonia, often from long\u2010term research, had larger sampling efforts, were published in higher impact factor journals and received more citations.\n                \n                \n                  We identified several gaps in the literature: 1) lack of acoustic surveys complementing mist\u2010netting, 2) telemetry studies were rare, 3) underrepresentation of the Caatinga biome, along with Pantanal and Grasslands (= Pampa), and 4) fewer studies using the landscape and fragment scale than local studies. We suggest that future research should focus on filling those gaps.\n                \n                \n                  Bat diversity is often found to be positively related to forest cover, fragment size and natural vegetation. Logging and agroforestry seem to have the lesser impact on bats compared to agriculture and urbanisation. Only haematophagous bats are benefited by pastures.\n                \n                \n                  We found guild\u2010specific responses to land\u2010use changes. Haematophagous batsseem to be the least impacted by them compared to other guilds, while animalivorous bats are particularly impacted by habitat fragmentation. Facing continuous deforestation, we can expect that bat diversity in Brazil will possibly reduce. Conservation efforts should focus on species shown to be sensitive to land\u2010use changes, especially where higher deforestation rates are expected.\n                \n              \n            \n          , \n            RESUMO EM PORTUGU\u00caS\n            \n              \n                \n                  Um ter\u00e7o do Brasil foi convertido em \u00e1reas antropizadas, enfatizando a necessidade de se entender as respostas da biodiversidade \u00e0s mudan\u00e7as no uso do solo. Para abordar esse problema, n\u00f3s revisamos 53 estudos sobre os efeitos das mudan\u00e7as no uso do solo em morcegos no pa\u00eds, publicados de 1990 at\u00e9 2018. Morcegos foram escolhidos porque eles contribuem para numerosos servi\u00e7os ecossist\u00eamicos, incluindo a dispers\u00e3o de sementes e o controle de insetos.\n                \n                \n                  Para cada estudo, n\u00f3s coletamos dados sobre o bioma onde o trabalho foi desenvolvido, institui\u00e7\u00f5es participantes, m\u00e9todo de amostragem, esfor\u00e7o amostral, principais resultados e impacto acad\u00eamico. As escalas espaciais dos estudos foram separadas em 'local', 'fragmento', 'paisagem' ou 'metapopula\u00e7\u00e3o'.\n                \n                \n                  Nossos resultados indicam um crescimento no interesse em morcegos e mudan\u00e7as no uso do solo com o passar do tempo; entretanto, nenhuma tend\u00eancia no impacto acad\u00eamico foi observada. Estudos desenvolvidos na Mata Atl\u00e2ntica foram mais comuns, aparecendo antes na literatura, mas estudos na Amaz\u00f4nia, frequentemente de longa dura\u00e7\u00e3o, tiveram maiores esfor\u00e7os amostrais, foram publicados em revistas com maior fator de impacto e receberam mais cita\u00e7\u00f5es.\n                \n                \n                  N\u00f3s identificamos v\u00e1rias lacunas na literatura: 1) falta de amostragens ac\u00fasticas complementando redes\u2010de\u2010neblina, 2) raros estudos com telemetria, 3) sub\u2010representa\u00e7\u00e3o do bioma Caatinga, assim como do Pantanal e do Pampa, e 4) poucos estudos usando as escalas de paisagem e fragmento em compara\u00e7\u00e3o com estudos locais. N\u00f3s sugerimos que pesquisas futuras foquem em reduzir essas lacunas.\n                \n                \n                  A diversidade de morcegos \u00e9 em geral positivamente relacionada com a cobertura florestal, tamanho do fragmento e vegeta\u00e7\u00e3o natural. A explora\u00e7\u00e3o madeireira e as agroflorestas parecem ter um impacto menor em morcegos quando comparadas com a agricultura e a urbaniza\u00e7\u00e3o. Apenas morcegos hemat\u00f3fagos s\u00e3o beneficiados por pastagens.\n                \n                \n                  N\u00f3s encontramos respostas espec\u00edficas por guilda para as mudan\u00e7as no uso do solo. Morcegos hemat\u00f3fagos parecem ser menos impactados por elas quando comparados com outras guildas, enquanto animal\u00edvoros s\u00e3o especialmente impactados pela fragmenta\u00e7\u00e3o de habitat. Diante do desmatamento cont\u00ednuo, n\u00f3s esperamos que a diversidade de morcegos no Brasil ir\u00e1 possivelmente reduzir. Esfor\u00e7os de conserva\u00e7\u00e3o devem focar em esp\u00e9cies indicadas como sens\u00edveis \u00e0s mudan\u00e7as no uso do solo, especialmente onde altas taxas de desmatamento s\u00e3o esperadas.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Mendes, Poliana", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Srbek\u2010Araujo, Ana Carolina", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/3d7ebf3b62fd80dc128883a9d314935f", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/dc20f5994b5fcdbf5e14362085090a8ea1f67a9683ad83a9de12ccd5112ec830", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/WIBIEJPD", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/WIBIEJPD", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/74d35e0fd1a27ea620eaae065e0f928b!/b352408-354910", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/26f7ce5dd404e33c6570edd4ba250d20", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class": ["Mammalia"], "dwc:kingdom": ["Animalia"], "dwc:order": ["Chiroptera"], "dwc:phylum": ["Chordata"]}, "resource_type": {"title": "Journal article", "type": "publication", "subtype": "article"}, "journal": {"issue": "1", "pages": "127-142", "title": "Mammal Review", "volume": "51"}, "alternate_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/3d7ebf3b62fd80dc128883a9d314935f"}, {"identifier": "urn:lsid:zotero.org:groups:5435545:items:WIBIEJPD"}, {"identifier": "10.1111/mam.12227"}], "communities": [{"id": "batlit"}, {"id": "b